      "description": "Vernacular cosmopolitanism represents the growing cultural phenomenon where local, indigenous, and 'ordinary' perspectives engage with global contexts while maintaining distinct identities. Unlike elite cosmopolitanism, this cluster captures how everyday citizens navigate global connections through local frameworks, developing hybrid cultural forms that are neither purely global nor purely local. It encompasses the rise of 'glocal' cultural productions, translation practices that preserve cultural specificity, and the increasing visibility of non-Western perspectives in global discourse. This cosmopolitanism 'from below' challenges traditional hierarchies of cultural value while creating new spaces for cross-cultural dialogue that respects difference rather than erasing it in pursuit of universalism.",
