      "description": "Counter mapping represents the critical cartographic practices that challenge dominant power structures embedded in conventional maps and mapping processes. It encompasses the creation of alternative spatial representations by marginalized communities, activists, artists, and scholars to contest official narratives, reclaim territorial knowledge, and visualize hidden socio-political realities. This movement has evolved from paper-based community mapping to sophisticated digital practices utilizing GIS, open-source tools, and participatory methodologies. Counter mapping operates at the intersection of critical geography, indigenous rights movements, environmental justice, urban activism, and digital humanities, serving as both analytical methodology and political praxis that reveals how space is produced through power relations and how alternative spatial imaginaries can foster social change.",
